<b><it>Amandla!: A Revolution in Four-Part Harmony</it></b> is a <link xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="../502/35502.xml">
2002</link> <link xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="../088/Intel_8088.xml">
documentary film</link> depicting the struggles of black <link xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="../221/17416221.xml">
South Africans</link> against the injustices of <link xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="../527/2200527.xml">
Apartheid</link> through the use of music. The film takes its name from the <ethnic_group wordnetid="107967382" confidence="0.9508927676800064">
<link xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="../216/66216.xml">
Xhosa</link></ethnic_group>
 and <ethnic_group wordnetid="107967382" confidence="0.9508927676800064">
<link xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="../427/34427.xml">
Zulu</link></ethnic_group>
 word <it><link xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="../752/3666752.xml">
amandla</link></it>, which means <it>power</it>.<p>

The film, directed by <link xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="../044/2165044.xml">
Lee Hirsch</link>, has been released as a <link xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="../621/46621.xml">
musical soundtrack</link> and a <medium wordnetid="106254669" confidence="0.9508927676800064">
<link xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="../498/11014498.xml">
DVD</link></medium>
 by <link xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="../674/996674.xml">
Lions Gate Films</link>. </p>

<sec>
<st>
Plot</st>
<p>

